Ford Gobike Trip data Exploration¶

by¶

Alex Mogengo¶

Introduction¶

  • This dataset contains 183412 entries of bike rides and 16 columns with various information about each bike ride trip.
  • The data row entry describes the duration of each bike ride trip in seconds, detailing the start time and the end time of the trip.
  • The data also has the start_station_id and end_station_id which uniquely identify the locations in which the users started and ended their bike rides.
  • There are also attached coordinates in terms of longitudes and latitudes of these unique locations
  • Each entry also has the unique identification of the bike used, the user type and their gender together with the year the user was born.

Main features¶

  • There are a number of key features which can help derive insights onto the dataset.
  • These include:
    • The start and end station IDs are import as they can give insights into which stations are preferred by users
    • The trip duration can also give insights into how long people get to ride the bikes, can be broken down gender-wise for further investigation.
    • Member birth year is also crucial to help analyze the ages of the bike users
    • The gender of the users can also be useful to our analysis
    • Age of the users

Bivariate Exploration¶

  • In this section I am going to focus on the how two of the features(variables) of the data relate to each other - bivariate.
  • In the dataset, the variables are of two types - numeric and categorical varibles.

  • The numeric variables include:

    • duration_sec

    • birth year

    • distance covered - new column

    • average speed - new column

Distance covered between the stations¶

In [28]:
## Create a distance covered column
## Will use theHaver Formula and and also use distancemetric & radians packages
# import the packages
from sklearn.neighbors import DistanceMetric
from math import radians

# define the haverseine_vectorize function to take the stand & end coordinates for the trips
def haversine_vectorize(start_station_longitude, start_station_latitude, end_station_longitude, end_station_latitude):
    start_station_longitude, start_station_latitude, end_station_longitude, end_station_latitude = map(np.radians, [start_station_longitude, start_station_latitude, end_station_longitude, end_station_latitude])
    
    # form the new longitudes from the the subtractions of the start and end
    newlon = end_station_longitude - start_station_longitude
    newlat = end_station_latitude - start_station_latitude
    
    # define the haver formula
    haver_formula = np.sin(newlat/2.0)**2 + np.cos(start_station_latitude) * np.cos(end_station_latitude) * np.sin(newlon/2.0)**2
    
    # calculate the distance in metres
    distance = 2* np.arcsin(np.sqrt(haver_formula))
    metres = 6367 * distance *1000
    
    return metres

# add a new column to have the distance covered by the bike users during the trips
go_bike['distance_covered'] = haversine_vectorize(go_bike['start_station_longitude'], go_bike['start_station_latitude'], go_bike['end_station_longitude'], go_bike['end_station_latitude'])

Year of birth and trip duration¶

  • The bike users born between 1975 and 1996 have the highest trip duration
  • Duration was low in the early years i.e below 1970s
  • There is high concentration of users past the 1980s
